Here is a JavaScript function that checks if a number is prime and then prints out the prime number if it's found in the array.

```javascript
function checkPrimeAndPrint(array) {
    // Check if array is not empty
    if (array.length < 5) {
        console.log('Array is too small to contain prime numbers.');
    } else {
        for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
            if (isPrime(array[i])) {
                console.log(array[i]);
            }
        }
    }
}

function isPrime(num) {
    // Function to check if a number is prime
    for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
        if (num % i === 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}
```

You can call this function with an array of 5 numbers as follows:

```javascript
let numbers = [2, 3, 5, 10, 17];
checkPrimeAndPrint(numbers);
```

The `isPrime()` function checks if a number is prime by iterating from 2 to the square root of the number. If the number is divisible by any number in this range, it's not prime. If the number isn't divisible by any number in this range, it is prime.

